data.content:
Use EF Core 7+'s **`ExecuteUpdateAsync`** and **`ExecuteDeleteAsync`** — they translate directly to SQL `UPDATE`/`DELETE` statements without loading entities into memory:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk update — single UPDATE statement
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6))
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s => s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk delete — single DELETE statement
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Why this fixes it:**

| | Before (load + save) | After (bulk) |
|---|---|---|
| SQL Statements | 500K+ / 2M+ | **1 each** |
| Memory | All entities tracked | **Zero entities loaded** |
| Round-trips | Thousands | **1 each** |

**Key notes:**
- These bypass the change tracker entirely — no `SaveChangesAsync()` needed
- They execute immediately (not deferred)
- Global query filters still apply; use `.IgnoreQueryFilters()` if needed
- If the DELETE on 2M rows causes lock escalation/timeouts, batch it:

```csharp
// Batched delete for very large sets
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```
